00:00:52,787 --> 00:00:56,455
narrator: the inuit and yupik native alaskan tribes invented 

6
00:00:56,457 --> 00:00:59,725
specialized goggles to prevent snow blindness.   

7
00:00:59,727 --> 00:01:01,660
in the early 20th century,   

8
00:01:01,662 --> 00:01:04,663
a new kind of eyewear was created for airline pilots 

9
00:01:04,665 --> 00:01:07,199
in order to protect their faces from wind.     

10
00:01:07,201 --> 00:01:09,735
soon, motorcyclists started wearing the eyewear      

11
00:01:09,737 --> 00:01:13,271
for the same purpose.     

12
00:01:13,273 --> 00:01:16,608
this manufacturer uses the same tooling process    

13
00:01:16,610 --> 00:01:19,078
used to produce the iconic eye protection   

14
00:01:19,080 --> 00:01:21,980
worn by the ace pilots of the royal air force     

15
00:01:21,982 --> 00:01:24,016
during world war ii.      

16
00:01:24,018 --> 00:01:26,485
production begins with a coil feeder,      

17
00:01:26,487 --> 00:01:30,489
which feeds a strip of soft-coil
brass into a press tool.    

18
00:01:30,491 --> 00:01:34,627
the tool stamps out a series of flat blanks.    

19
00:01:34,629 --> 00:01:38,096
the press simultaneously punches
two guide holes        

20
00:01:38,098 --> 00:01:42,501
that will help position the blanks on the other tools. 

21
00:01:42,503 --> 00:01:44,903
two raised press tools form the blank           

22
00:01:44,905 --> 00:01:48,307
around a left and right die.  

23
00:01:48,309 --> 00:01:52,445
the press tools add new folds and contours to the blanks.  

24
00:01:55,316 --> 00:01:58,684
another press tool stamps out the center aperture.      

25
00:02:01,455 --> 00:02:03,656
a device punches out stitching holes        

26
00:02:03,658 --> 00:02:05,458
that will allow an attachment 

27
00:02:05,460 --> 00:02:08,327
to connect to a leather face pad.     

28
00:02:08,329 --> 00:02:10,996
a different press tool punctures
the stitching holes      

29
00:02:10,998 --> 00:02:13,799
located along the goggle frame.

30
00:02:13,801 --> 00:02:15,734
due to the age of the machinery,

31
00:02:15,736 --> 00:02:19,337
the distance between the holes has become slightly uneven,  

32
00:02:19,339 --> 00:02:22,074
giving the goggles their distinctive character.  

33
00:02:24,144 --> 00:02:28,280
next, the nose-bridge bracket is positioned on a rivet shaft.

34
00:02:28,282 --> 00:02:30,015
with the eyepiece in place,  

35
00:02:30,017 --> 00:02:31,751
the craftsman triggers the device           

36
00:02:31,753 --> 00:02:34,086
to rivet the components together.    

37
00:02:34,088 --> 00:02:36,555
before he attaches the two eyepieces,       

38
00:02:36,557 --> 00:02:39,891
the craftsman polishes each piece against a grinding wheel.

39
00:02:39,893 --> 00:02:41,827
this is a two-step process   

40
00:02:41,829 --> 00:02:44,563
starting with an operation called scarfing,        

41
00:02:44,565 --> 00:02:46,565
which prepares the surface,  

42
00:02:46,567 --> 00:02:49,635
followed by polishing with a special compound.    

43
00:02:51,972 --> 00:02:54,640
the goggle lenses will be installed into the frames   

44
00:02:54,642 --> 00:02:56,776
at a 45-degree angle,     

45
00:02:56,778 --> 00:03:00,712
so a grinding wheel casts a 22.5-degree angle      

46
00:03:00,714 --> 00:03:03,048
on each section of glass.   

47
00:03:03,050 --> 00:03:05,517
the craftswoman removes the slight burr        

48
00:03:05,519 --> 00:03:08,921
left by the grinding process with a sanding wheel.     

49
00:03:08,923 --> 00:03:11,257
the lenses are made out of shatterproof laminate     

50
00:03:11,259 --> 00:03:13,592
for additional protection.   

51
00:03:13,594 --> 00:03:17,463
the lens frame is made out of a painted brass channel.  

52
00:03:17,465 --> 00:03:19,999
the brass has been annealed for strength          

53
00:03:20,001 --> 00:03:24,202
and to remove any internal stresses.     

54
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:27,873
a small rod is inserted as a temporary support.    

55
00:03:27,875 --> 00:03:30,208
she places the assembly in a clamp           

56
00:03:30,210 --> 00:03:33,512
and secures the channel in place
with a brass cleat.      

57
00:03:36,884 --> 00:03:39,684
she uses a manual hand press to bend the channel      

58
00:03:39,686 --> 00:03:43,288
to 45 degrees.         

59
00:03:43,290 --> 00:03:46,025
the craftswoman removes the support rod        

60
00:03:46,027 --> 00:03:47,493
and applies epoxy glue     

61
00:03:47,495 --> 00:03:51,430
to the seam between the two sections of glass.   

62
00:03:51,432 --> 00:03:55,367
she inserts a brass cleat to hold the assembly in place, 

63
00:03:55,369 --> 00:03:56,836
and this time the cleat    

64
00:03:56,838 --> 00:04:00,172
is permanently fastened to the assembly.        

65
00:04:00,174 --> 00:04:05,844
now the eyepiece is ready for the next phase of production. 

66
00:04:05,846 --> 00:04:08,514
the eyepieces are attached to a leather face pad     

67
00:04:08,516 --> 00:04:11,784
made from lamb nappa leather. 

68
00:04:11,786 --> 00:04:13,919
a craftsperson starts the process          

69
00:04:13,921 --> 00:04:15,788
by using a custom die     

70
00:04:15,790 --> 00:04:20,993
and a 10-ton press       
to stamp out the required shape.

71
00:04:20,995 --> 00:04:23,863
then she uses a leatherworking sewing machine         

72
00:04:23,865 --> 00:04:27,266
to stitch the two layers of the face pad together.   

73
00:04:27,268 --> 00:04:31,270
with exactly 1.5 millimeters between each stitch,      

74
00:04:31,272 --> 00:04:32,872
the attachment is durable   

75
00:04:32,874 --> 00:04:35,174
without overperforating the leather.          

76
00:04:37,812 --> 00:04:40,412
she sews the inner perimeter of the face mask        

77
00:04:40,414 --> 00:04:43,481
with an overlocking stitch.  

78
00:04:43,483 --> 00:04:45,551
this operation is not easy.  

79
00:04:45,553 --> 00:04:48,954
it takes a skilled leatherworker
up to seven months of training 

80
00:04:48,956 --> 00:04:51,023
to become truly proficient.  

81
00:04:55,229 --> 00:04:58,830
before sewing the nose-cover section of the face pad,    

82
00:04:58,832 --> 00:05:01,567
the craftswoman glues the layers together      

83
00:05:01,569 --> 00:05:03,969
to ensure they're assembled correctly.  

84
00:05:07,041 --> 00:05:08,974
after the glue has cured,   

85
00:05:08,976 --> 00:05:13,579
the goggle eyepieces are placed
in position over the face pad, 

86
00:05:13,581 --> 00:05:16,382
and the components are stitched together by hand. 

87
00:05:20,654 --> 00:05:23,322
the goggle assembly is almost complete.      

88
00:05:26,928 --> 00:05:29,394
the goggle lenses are placed into position         

89
00:05:29,396 --> 00:05:32,531
in the channels of the eyepiece frames.    

90
00:05:32,533 --> 00:05:36,669
now they just need to be secured in place.       

91
00:05:36,671 --> 00:05:39,071
the headband clips attach to the goggles         

92
00:05:39,073 --> 00:05:41,139
and lock in the lenses.    

93
00:05:41,141 --> 00:05:44,877
not only do these handcrafted goggles protect your face,   

94
00:05:44,879 --> 00:05:47,847
you can be assured       
they will never go out of style.

95
00:05:55,623 --> 00:06:01,427
